# DB2 Query via MCP Tool — Usage Rules

## CRITICAL: Default Database Warning

When `databaseName` is empty or omitted, the tool defaults to **`BASISRAP` (PRODUCTION)**.

**Always specify `databaseName` explicitly.** When the user does not specify a database, ASK which one before running. Never assume.

## Setup

The `db2-query` MCP server runs on `dedge-server` (IIS). Developers register it once:

```powershell
pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "c:\opt\src\CursorDb2McpServer\Register-McpServer.ps1"
```

Cursor config (`~/.cursor/mcp.json`):

```json
{ "mcpServers": { "db2-query": { "url": "http://dedge-server/CursorDb2McpServer/" } } }
```

## Correct Usage

Always read `mcps/user-db2-query/tools/query_db2.json` before calling.

```json
{ "server": "user-db2-query", "toolName": "query_db2",
  "arguments": { "databaseName": "BASISTST", "query": "SELECT ..." } }
```

## Common Mistakes — Detect and Correct

| Mistake | What the agent MUST do |
|---------|----------------------|
| No `databaseName` specified | ASK the user which database. Never default silently to BASISRAP. |
| Using `db2-query` as server name | Use `user-db2-query` (Cursor prefixes user MCP servers with `user-`) |
| Sending INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE | STOP. The tool is read-only. Tell the user this is not allowed. |
| Using `url` like `http://...8480/mcp` | The correct URL is `http://dedge-server/CursorDb2McpServer/` (port 80, no `/mcp`) |
| Forgetting `FETCH FIRST n ROWS ONLY` on large tables | WARN the user and add the clause. Unlimited queries can return huge results. |
| Writing results to file without encoding | Use `-Encoding windows-1252` (PowerShell) or `encoding='cp1252'` (Python) |

